SIMPLE: gust
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gust
<hw>Gust</hw> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel.
<ets>gustr</ets> a cool breeze. Cf. <er>Gush</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A sudden squall; a violent blast of wind; a sudden and brief
rushing or driving of the wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Snow, and hail, stormy <qex>gust</qex> and flaw.</q>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sudden violent burst of passion.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gust
<hw>Gust</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>gustus</ets>; cf. It. & Sp.
<ets>gusto</ets>. ⟦root⟧46.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The sense or pleasure of tasting; relish;
gusto.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An ox will relish the tender flesh of kids with as much
<qex>gust</qex> and appetite.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Gratification of any kind, particularly that which
is exquisitely relished; enjoyment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Destroy all creatures for thy sport or <qex>gust.</qex></q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Intellectual taste; fancy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A choice of it may be made according to the gust and manner of the
ancients.</q> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gust
<hw>Gust</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>gustare</ets>, It.
<ets>gustare</ets>, Sp. <ets>gustar</ets>. See <er>GUST</er> a
relish.]</ety> <def>To taste; to have a relish for.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gustable</ent>⟦br⟧
